content.description: Follow the obvious crack that has a bush half way to the top.
content.protection: small to medium nuts and tri cams. Number 2 cam toward the top.
content.location: Located on Tree tower. If looking at the main Tree tower route it is to the left. If looking at the access route it is to the right. Descend off the access route or rappel the tree down the bowlers grip route.

content.description: Start at lowest point. Climb northeast ridge on nice ledges to a sweet lieback at the top. Be careful of loose and brittle rock near and on top. Descend at route 3.
content.protection: Setting a toprope: take the south side of the tower (descent route) to the top. Use east side of tower to set up. See my anchor photo below.

content.description: Climb thin crack past small overhang. To the right of flying Indian, Page 296 #21 in 3rd edition DL guidebook
content.protection: Trees at top, small to medium gear
content.location: Tree Tower. Wall to the north of Tree Tower. To the right of flying Indian

content.description: Would be three stars if it was taller but there were some great finger locks.
content.location: Located on the right side of the wall. It is the obvious crack left of a blank face.

content.description: Up the buttress, to the right of the alcove.  An easy romp with nice exposure.
content.location: On Tree Tower Wall, north of Tree Tower, south of the flat, smooth face with Flying Indian crack.

content.description: start on west face of tower,continue up the crack to the left handed bowlers grip, then gravy the rest of the way.
content.protection: Standard rack,Use route 3 5.2 for access to top rope,when on top use small to medium cams with a cord.

content.description: Simple and direct, this route gives access to the top of the tower. The vertical crack on left can be used as a variation.
content.protection: A large cam or two.  Use a standard rack and cordolette for the anchor.

content.description:
The Tree Tower area is hardly used by climbers.  Lots of moderate climbs.The Tree Tower Wall has 50-70 foot routes, while the tower itself has 40-60 foot routes.  WEAR YOUR HELMET!  Bunch of loose rock on both the tower and the access.  Even though its part of the summit band, its very shady.

 See Tree Tower for boulder problems on this formation!
